A cirulant matrix defines a discrete convolution:

**Definition (discrete convolution)**
The _discrete convolution_ of two vectors is given by
$$
ūĚźö ‚čÜ ūĚźü := L[a] ūĚźü,
$$
i.e.,
$$
(ūĚźö * ūĚźü)[k] = ‚ąĎ_{j=1}^n a_{k-j} f_{j-1}
$$
where we define $a_{-j} := a_j$.

The analogue between this discsrete convolution and the continuous convolution is immediate, and this can be thought of as a discretisation of the continuous convolution using a trapezium rule.

## Diagonalising convolutions

Note that $S$ is an orthogonal matrix, in particular we can verify
$$
S^{-1} = S^‚ä§ = \begin{bmatrix}
0 & 1 \\
 && ‚čĪ \\
 &&& 1 \\
 1 \end{bmatrix}
$$
We can thus write
$$
L[a] = a_0 + S^{-1} a_1 + ‚čĮ + S^{1-n} a_{n-1}
$$
It follows that diagonalising $S$ (and therefore $S^{-1}$) allows us to diagonalise and circulant matrix. The nice property is that the DFT diagonalises $S$:

**Proposition (diagonalising $S$)**
$$
S Q_n = Q_n \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ & ‚čĪ && ŌČ^{n-1} \end{matrix]
$$
where $Q_n$ is the DFT matrix and $ŌČ = \E^{2ŌÄ\I/n}$.

**Proof**

We can verify that the columns of $Q_n$ are eigenvectors of $S$:
$$
S \Vectt[1, ŌČ^k , \dots, ŌČ^{k(n-1)}] = \Vectt[ŌČ^k , \dots, ŌČ^{k(n-1),1] = 
ŌČ^k \Vectt[1, ŌČ^k , \dots, ŌČ^{k(n-1)}],
$$
since we have $ŌČ^k ŌČ^{k(n-1)} = ŌČ^{kn} 1$.

‚ąé

This immediately gives us a diagonalisation of circulant matrices:

**Theorem (diagonalising circulants)**
For
$$
a(őł) = a_0 + a_1 \E^{\I őł} + ‚Ä¶ + a_{n-1} \E^{\I (n-1) őł}
$$
we have
$$
L[a] Q_n = Q_n \begin{bmatrix} a(1) \\ & ‚čĪ && a(ŌČ^{1-n}) \end{matrix]
$$

**Proof**

We see directly
$$
L[a] = ‚ąĎ_{k=0}^{n-1} a_k S^{-k} = 
‚ąĎ_{k=0}^{n-1} a_k Q_n begin{bmatrix}1 \\ & ‚čĪ && ŌČ^{k(1-n)} \end{matrix] Q_n^‚čÜ.
$$


